<HEADLINE>
FT  22 AUG 92 / Letter: Reducing PSBR would spur private rented sector
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr RICHARD MCMANUS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Prof Gavin McCrone probably over-estimates the need for tax concessions
to revitalise the private residential rented sector (August 17).
A comparison between net rental yields at around 6 per cent and gilt yields
at 9.5 per cent suggests investment in residential rental property is a poor
option. Yet long-term rental payments and property values are inflation
linked.
A London flat with a current open market value of Pounds 75,000 could be let
to produce a net rental yield of around Pounds 4,500 a year. With modest
inflation and if interest rates fall, the value of the flat increases. If
the rental income stream and the open market value of the flat increase by 3
per cent a year over 25 years, the net present value would be about Pounds
112,000, with a discount rate of only 6 per cent.
This compares favourably with a Pounds 108,000 net present value of Pounds
75,000 of gilts yielding 9.5 per cent over 25 years with the same discount
rate.
It is only if the government eliminates inflation that gilts are a far
better bet, and fully funding the PSBR 'crowds out' necessary institutional
investment in residential rental property. But reducing government borrowing
must be better than compensating tax concessions.
Richard McManus,
44 Upham Park Road,
London W4
</TEXT>
