<HEADLINE>
FT  22 AUG 92 / UN team urges moretroops for Somalia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIAN OZANNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NAIROBI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A CONFIDENTIAL United Nations report has recommended that at least a further
1,000 armed UN guards be sent urgently to protect aid efforts in Somalia,
with or without the consent of the warring factions.
The controversial recommendation, soon to be put to the Security Council, is
made by a UN team which recently visited Somalia. It is likely to antagonise
most of Somalia's feuding warlords, who have threatened to fire on UN troops
who enter the country without their agreement.
The unpublished report says more armed UN guards are necessary to help
relief efforts reach an estimated 1.5m people facing starvation in a country
where banditry and looting is widespread. An agreement was clinched last
week, after months of obstruction by one Somali military faction, to allow
500 UN guards to protect relief operations, but they are confined to
Mogadishu.
The report recommends that every effort should be made to reach agreement
with the warring factions for the deployment of more UN security personnel.
But it adds: 'In the event that no agreement is reached the UN should be
prepared to do so without the consent of the parties.'
The report goes on: 'The essential point is that the international community
cannot stand idly and witness the unnecessary loss of human lives in
Somalia.'
The UN report says at least 500 troops should be dispatched to both
north-east and south-west Somalia to protect humanitarian relief operations
and safeguard ports, airports and road convoys.
It says the troops should be armed with light weapons, armour-breaking
weapons, teargas and rubber bullets and have armoured personnel carriers.
The report suggests the two battalions should be based in Bossaso, in the
far north-east, and Mandera, a Kenyan town on the Somali border.
The report, which was presented to Mr Boutros Boutros Ghali, the
secretary-general, on Wednesday, also recommends the deployment of further
military observers in the north-east, south-west and southern regions of
Somalia. Fifty military observers are already in Mogadishu.
Other recommendations include:
The creation, under UN auspices, of a disarming force which would carry out
a 'food for arms' exchange programme.
The division of the country into four operational zones.
Delivering 39,000 tonnes of food relief each month.
The provision of assistance in re-establishing a police force.
A non-food aid programme, covering health, water, sanitation, agriculture
and livestock.
Meanwhile, US and Kenyan officials scrambled to limit the damage after a
bruising diplomatic row about the massive US airlift of food to Somalia.
US Ambassador Smith Hempstone and the US general in charge of the airlift
were summoned for a hurried meeting with President Daniel arap Moi after the
Kenyan government protested that the US had flouted Kenyan sovereignty and
had not sought proper clearance to send armed troops on to Kenyan soil.
Mr Ndolo Ayah, the Kenyan foreign minister, said President Moi had now
authorised the first flight of the airlift to Wajir, northern Kenya, and the
US and Kenya had established a committee to co-ordinate all details of the
relief effort.
</TEXT>
