<HEADLINE>
FT  21 AUG 92 / Money Markets: Futures rally
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
SHORT-DATED sterling fut-ures rallied yesterday morning after the Bundesbank
refrained from changing the emergency Lombard rate at its council meeting,
and the figure for Germany's July M3 money supply came in at 8.6 per cent.
But, as has happened several times this week, the mood of futures dealers
did an about-turn in the afternoon. Futures contracts dipped to their
opening levels as the dollar fell at the start of foreign exchange trading
in the US and sterling declined with it.
The September short sterling contract jumped 6 basis points from its opening
level of 89.66 after the Bundesbank signalled no change in rates at its
fortnightly meeting.
One commercial bank dealer also interpreted the M3 money supply figure as
positive. He noted that the figure was 0.1 per cent lower than the previous
month's monetary growth. This was particularly good, he said, since the
effects of the recent 0.75 of a percentage point rise in the discount rate
have not yet worked through the German banking system.
In the afternoon, futures prices fell as the pound sank to DM2.8075, its
lowest point since Britain joined the ERM. The September contract finished
one basis point down at 89.64, and the December contract was off 4 basis
points at 89.64. Some dealers felt that these were probably the bottom
levels for the front-month contracts unless a rise in UK base rates looks
imminent.
Trade in the sterling cash market was thin. As often happens on a Thursday,
dealers took most of the day to take out the shortage forecast by the Bank
of England. This is because traders like to offer large numbers of bills to
the Bank of England on a Friday when they can push the overnight rate down
as far as possible for the weekend.
In the morning, the Bank forecast a shortage of Pounds 1.05bn. In early
operations, the Bank bought Pounds 31m of Band 1 Treasury bills and Pounds
20m of Band 1 bank bills at 9 7/8 per cent. The forecast was later revised
to Pounds 1bn and the bank purchased Pounds 36m in Band 1 bank bills, and
Pounds 91m in a repurchase agreement at 9 15/16 per cent. The Bank then
bought Pounds 14m in Band 1 Treasury bills, Pounds 694m in Band 1 Bank
bills, Pounds 2m in Band 2 Treasury bills and Pounds 1m in Band 2 bank
bills. There was late assistance of Pounds 120m.
</TEXT>
