<HEADLINE>
FT  21 AUG 92 / International Bonds: Canadian new issue activity stalls
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TRACY CORRIGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A STRONG rally in the Canadian government bond market yesterday sparked
expectations of supply in the Euro-Canadian sector. However, poor swap
conditions and a lack of borrowers requiring Canadian dollar funding have
temporarily stalled new issue activity.
Canadian dollar Eurobond spreads widened as government bond yields fell
faster than Eurobond yields, while swap spreads remained tight.
'The market has almost rallied too far (for Eurobond issuance),' said one
syndicate official. The Canadian sector of the Eurobond market has
traditionally had a substantial retail investor base, viewing the market as
a high-yielding alternative to US dollars. With coupons for 10-year Canadian
Eurobonds likely to be in the region of 7 1/2 per cent to 7 3/4 per cent,
the market is no longer an obvious buy for European retail investors, who
must now be persuaded that the currency is set to appreciate, dealers said.
The steep yield curve means that shorter-dated deals will offer even lower
yields.
Meanwhile, Credit Foncier de France added a further Dollars 50m to its
Dollars 150m issue of floating-rate notes launched on Wednesday, on a
quieter day for the recently hectic floating-rate sector, as the market
absorbed Wednesday's Dollars 500m offering by BankAmerica.
The Royal Bank of Scotland has increased its Dollars 200m issue of
preference share capital, launched on August 3, to Dollars 400m, making it
the largest overseas bank issue in the US preference share market.
'This issue reinforces the strength of our capital base in a very
cost-effective way,' said Mr Kenneth Thompson, group finance director of the
Royal Bank. The shares, which pay a dividend of 9 1/2 per cent, qualify as
tier 1 capital under international bank capital guidelines which come into
force next year.
Guinness has set up a Dollars 1bn programme, which provides for the issuance
of listed Eurobonds as well as medium-term notes. The multi-currency
programme, arranged by Morgan Stanley International, includes a D-Mark
option.
The company, which will use the programme to refinance short-term debt,
expects to start issuing paper under the programme in the latter part of
September.
</TEXT>
