<HEADLINE>
FT  21 AUG 92 / International Company News: O&amp;Y beats a gruelling path to
Toronto court door - Bernard Simon examines the immediate prospects of
restructuring the Canadian property developer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
After five gruelling months of negotiations and court appearances, a note of
frustration is creeping into efforts to revive Olympia &amp; York, the ailing
multi-national property developer.
O&amp;Y, whose Canadian and UK assets have been under court protection since
May, is required to file a restructuring plan for most of its CDollars
13.5bn (USDollars 11.27bn) debt with an Ontario judge this morning. Its 25
buildings in the US remain outside court protection.
In a preview of the plan, Mr Gerald Greenwald, O&amp;Y president, and Mr Steve
Miller, chief negotiator, disclosed yesterday that creditors are being
offered up to 80 per cent of O&amp;Y's equity, including voting control.
Maturity dates on most project loans as well as a Dollars 2.5bn jumbo loan
would be extended.
O&amp;Y's owners, the Reichmann family, are also willing to contribute their
directly held 20 per cent stake in O&amp;Y's US operations to the restructured
company, as well as a number of family-owned buildings in Canada.
Mr Greenwald, Mr Miller and their colleagues have held about 40 meetings
with various groups of creditors in the past month. They put a brave face
yesterday on the progress so far, saying that agreement in principle is
close with lenders to five of O&amp;Y's 11 major Canadian projects.
Mr Miller said: 'The progress and the movement have been good in all cases.'
The creditors however, paint a more sombre picture. 'No one is even close
(to an agreement),' says one institutional lender.
Noting that O&amp;Y has so far made 'a series of piecemeal offers to various
creditors', a senior Toronto bankruptcy lawyer concludes: 'There must be
some serious problems.'
To no one's great surprise, the restructuring is proving more complex than
expected. Layers of secrecy which once surrounded the Reichmann family
empire have been peeled away to reveal a highly centralised management
structure, but a financial structure which was just the opposite.
Mr Greenwald said yesterday that negotiations are taking place with 27
separate groups of creditors. Each O&amp;Y building is a separate entity with
its own financing arrangements.
Some are in a healthy financial condition, providing more than adequate
security for their creditors. Others have rising vacancy rates, ebbing cash
flow and falling market values, with the added complication of various
layers of creditors, each fighting to protect its own interests.
Much of the past few months has been spent trying to reconcile competing
interests. Creditors have had to be slotted into one or more of six creditor
committees. Much time has been spent apportioning overheads and
restructuring costs among O&amp;Y's various projects.
Asset sales have slowed to a snail's pace. The latest report from Price
Waterhouse, which acts as a conduit for information between O&amp;Y and its
creditors, notes that, besides the disposal of a Gulfstream jet, O&amp;Y has in
the past month raised a paltry CDollars 3.7m from Canadian government bonds
and a vendor take-back mortgage. A deal to dispose of its interest in a
12-storey office project in Budapest has fallen through. The sale of Home
Oil of Calgary, which was said to be imminent even before O&amp;Y sought court
protection, has yet to be concluded.
Despite these hitches, few are willing to predict where O&amp;Y is heading after
today's court appearance. Some lenders are talking darkly of bankruptcy and
liquidation, or of reviving efforts to 'carve out' individual buildings from
the protection of the courts.
Although the US operations are not in bankruptcy protection, bondholders of
55 Water Street, a mammoth New York office building, are considering
proposals to replace O&amp;Y as manager and to bring in a new investor with the
resources to pay for asbestos removal and other improvements.
Creditors are also increasingly edgy about the spiralling costs of the
restructuring effort. The Canadian operations paid CDollars 3.5m in July to
investment bankers, lawyers and accountants, and expect to fork out another
CDollars 4.8m this month.
Price Waterhouse estimates that the costs of creditor committees are running
at another CDollars 2m a month. Sensing these concerns, Mr Miller said the
company plans to cut general and administrative expenses by 70 per cent.
O&amp;Y is still banking that its reputation as a first-rate manager of
buildings will discourage creditors from pulling the plug, especially during
an un-remitting slump in the North American commercial property market. A
lawyer for one bank says he senses that the lenders are 'more malleable'
than they were a month ago.
The scales could be tipped by the fate of the Canary Wharf development in
London. Mr Paul Reichmann is negotiating to regain a foothold in the
Docklands project through an investor group which includes US financiers Mr
Laurence Tisch, Mr Sanford Weil and Mr Lewis Ranieri. Investors would
contribute Pounds 350m (Dollars 678.65m) and O&amp;Y would continue to manage
the project.
Some participants in the restructuring predict that O&amp;Y's chances of keeping
its creditors at bay in the US and Canada will improve significantly if the
Canary Wharf lenders and administrators throw their support behind the
Reichmann-led Docklands bid.
Conversely, rejection of the Canary Wharf bid could weaken the confidence of
lenders in North America that the rest of the Reichmann empire is worth
preserving.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 19
</PAGE>
