<HEADLINE>
FT  21 AUG 92 / International Company News: Equitable secures new credit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Equitable Life Assurance Society of New York, the large but troubled
life insurer in which France's Axa group now owns a 49 per cent stake, said
yesterday that it had secured a new Dollars 550m credit facility.
The back-up loan facility is being provided by a 13-strong international
syndicate of banks, led by Chase Manhattan, and will last for 364 days. The
Equitable said that it replaced a Dollars 1.16bn facility, which was never
used and intended primarily to support commercial paper sales. 'We have no
plans to borrow against the new line,' Mr Richard Jenrette, Equitable's
chairman, said.
There were reports this month that The Equitable had been unable to arrange
a Dollars 600m credit line, and was cutting the amount sought and maturity
desired.
In order to bolster its capital, The Equitable converted from mutual status
to a conventional shareholder-owned company. Axa invested Dollars 1bn for
its 49 per cent stake, but when The Equitable tried to raise additional
money through the general flotation of its shares, it was obliged to cut the
offering price from Dollars 11-Dollars 14 to Dollars 9.
