<HEADLINE>
FT  21 AUG 92 / Delay in recovery to 1994 forecast
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN faces four more quarters of negative growth with a recovery delayed
until 1994, Professor Doug McWilliams, economic adviser to the Confederation
of British Industry, said yesterday.
The prediction by one of the UK's leading economists - speaking for himself
and not on behalf of the CBI - is far gloomier than most published City
forecasts. It underlines growing fears about a long period of economic
inertia.
Prof McWilliams, who has a high reputation at the Treasury, predicts that
the economy will contract by 1 per cent this year, after a fall of 2.4 per
cent last year. He thinks gross domestic product will be flat next year and
expand 2 per cent in 1994.
Prof McWilliams said inflation was likely to fall to 2 per cent next year
and 1 per cent in 1994.
He set out his views in a report published by the Chartered Institute of
Marketing - an organisation to which he is economic adviser, a post separate
from his role at the CBI.
The consensus among City economists for this year is that the economy will
shrink by about 0.5 per cent, followed by a modest upturn in 1993. The CBI's
latest published forecast is for 1 per cent growth this year, followed by
expansion of 3 per cent next year.
Prof McWilliams said his prediction of no growth next year followed from
what he predicted will be fragile economic activity in the second half of
this year.
'Businesses are likely to cut back on spending, while consumer demand will
remain weak,' he said.
'1993 is going to start with Britain in quite a depressed position, with
many companies looking exposed.'
Prof McWilliams said growth should start to pick up about mid-1993, with
businesses rather than consumers being responsible for most of the upturn.
High mortgages coupled with rising unemployment and weak house prices would
be likely to put a clamp on spending, he said in the institute's report.
Even though businesses faced problems over the next year, three potential
sources of growth were likely by 1994, Prof McWilliams predicted. Falling
costs would continue to improve companies' cash positions, exports were
likely to grow and the privatised utility companies should have large
investment programmes coming on stream that would add to demand.
</TEXT>
