FT  21 AUG 92 / Retirement benefits stressed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT is trying to contrast favourably the treatment of British
pensioners with their Continental counterparts as it embarks on further
consultations over its plans to equalise retirement ages for men and women.
The government's message is that British pensioners fare well by European
standards when comparing all services provided and not just the cash value
of pensions. Miss Ann Widdecombe, junior social security minister, said
yesterday: 'European comparisons simply based on cash value take us
nowhere.'
The timing of the initiative will increase speculation that the government
intends to equalise the state retirement age at 65 - a move seen as
politically unpalatable because it would require women to work five years
longer before being entitled to benefit.
The Social Security Advisory Committee, the government's adviser on pensions
policy, this month came out in favour of such a move. It suggested the
Pounds 3bn annual savings could be used to help pensioners penalised by low
pay and interrupted service in their working lives.
Miss Widdecombe, stressing that the government had still not decided between
the options for equalising state pension ages it set out last year, said she
was concerned that current discussions should mark the start of a longer
debate about how best to meet the needs of future generations of pensioners.
</TEXT>
