<HEADLINE>
FT  21 AUG 92 / OFT asks for details of credit-card pricing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BANKS AND building societies are bracing themselves for a fresh
investigation by the Office of Fair Trading into the pricing of their credit
and debit card services.
The OFT has written to them asking for detailed technical information about
the way they run their credit card pricing systems.
The organisations have until the end of next week to provide the
information. Several say the OFT's request - which follows a series of
submissions from large food retailers - is so detailed that the deadline
cannot met.
The investigation is the latest in a series by the OFT in the past 14 years.
It has twice referred the problem to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission
for inquiries, the last of which reported three years ago. Neither
investigation resulted in radical changes in the industry.
The latest investigation is the most disturbing for the banks since
retailers have succeeded in focusing the OFT's attention on the two main
elements in the credit card business: 'merchant acquiring' - the handling of
retailer card transactions - and the interchange fee, the fixed charge paid
by a retailer's bank to the cardholder's bank each time the card is used.
The changes that retailers are pressing for would produce a transformation
of the credit card industry.
Five supermarkets have pressed the OFT to allow them to handle their own
transactions. The rules of Visa International and MasterCard International
prevent the retailers from doing this by barring non-bank organisations.
The retailers' moves follow increases in January in the commissions they pay
to banks.
The OFT letter, signed by Mr Andre Hook of the competition policy division,
says retailers believe the increase in charges follows a rise in the
interchange fee.
</TEXT>
