<HEADLINE>
FT  21 AUG 92 / Finland proposes budget cut of FM6bn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Finnish government yesterday proposed swingeing cuts worth nearly FM6bn
(Pounds 776m) in next year's budget. This decision follows cuts agreed in
June totalling an estimated FM7bn.
The cabinet was forced to make further downward revisions in its spending
programmes for 1993 because of a soaring budget deficit, fuelled by the cost
of growing unemployment, which the government estimates will average 13 per
cent in 1993, and provisions by the state of FM20.8bn this year to rescue
the ailing banking sector from collapse,
The latest cuts will involve a 4 per cent reduction in central and local
government administrative costs as well as savings from reduced expenditure
on transport, agriculture, housing and provision of child care facilities.
The numbers entitled to unemployment benefit will be reduced. In addition
the cabinet announced rises in energy taxes to double the yield to FM1bn,
further damping depressed domestic demand.
The latest bout of cuts was decided by the cabinet which sat late into the
night. They underline the continuing fragility of Finland's economy despite
an improvement in its export performance, low inflation and signs of a
recovery in profitability in both the metal and forestry sectors.
Continuing high market interest rates reflect persistent international
unease about the economy, although Mr Michel Camdessus, head of the
International Monetary Fund, took a positive view of its future on a visit
to Finland recently.
The markets are looking apprehensively to next month's centralised wage
negotiations, where employers are seeking a three-year deal with no pay
rises, which the trade unions are unlikely to accept.
In October Prime Minister Esko Aho and colleagues in the Centre
party-Conservative coalition face a test of their political popularity with
local government elections. Observers believe that if these turn out to be
disastrous for the ruling parties it could precipitate a political crisis
and possible change of government.
The current concern is the likely size of the public deficit, expected to
rise by FM68bn this year to FM185bn. ETLA, the country's independent
economic forecasters, believe public debt will level off by 1996 to around
50 per cent of gross domestic product.
</TEXT>
