<HEADLINE>
FT  21 AUG 92 / Sterling falls to lowest ERM levelagainst D-Mark: Decline
partly driven by drop in dollar
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ and DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
STERLING fell yesterday to its lowest level against the D-Mark on the
foreign exchanges since Britain joined the European exchange rate mechanism
in October 1990.
The pound's  1/2 pfennig fall in London, to close at DM2.8070, left it
within three pfennigs of its permitted floor against the D-Mark in the ERM.
In New York it dipped further to DM2.8057.
If it reaches the lower limit of DM2.7780, the government will be forced to
support the currency either by intervention on the foreign exchanges, or by
raising interest rates.
The pound's fall yesterday was partly driven by the decline of the dollar,
as dealers sold the US currency in exchange for D-Marks on speculation that
the Bundesbank's high interest rate policy will remain for some time.
The dollar fell to a low of DM1.4455, narrowly above its all-time low of
DM1.4430 reached in February 1991. It closed in London at DM1.4485, down
nearly  1/2 pfennig on the day, and slipped to DM1.4475 in New York.
Expectations that the German central bank will keep its short-term interest
rates high were triggered by its latest figure for money supply growth,
indicating that inflationary pressures in Germany remained strong.
The broad money M3 measure grew at an annualised rate of 8.6 per cent
between the fourth quarter of 1991 and last month, compared with 8.7 per
cent in June.
Although the trend in money supply growth is downwards, the Bundesbank's
target growth rate of 3.5 per cent to 5.5 per cent for the year appears
likely to be missed. That makes improbable an imminent relaxation in the
German central bank's tight monetary policy.
Investors also switched funds out of sterling on concern about the UK's
recovery prospects. Yesterday Professor Doug McWilliams, economic adviser to
the Confederation of British Industry, said Britain faced four more quarters
of contraction with a recovery delayed until 1994. He predicted a 1 per cent
fall in output this year, followed by zero growth next year. Many foreign
exchange dealers believe that the US Federal Reserve and the Bank of England
are likely to buy their currencies on the foreign exchanges if the decline
in the dollar and the pound continues.
However, the two rounds of central bank intervention in support of the
dollar over the past month have failed to stop the US currency's slide.
Although the Bundesbank Council meeting concluded yesterday without a change
in interest rate policy, the market is still fearful of a rise in the
internationally sensitive Lombard rate following the increase in the
discount rate.
Money market interest rates in Germany are at around the same level as the
9.75 per cent Lombard rate. In the past, the Bundesbank has used this as an
excuse for raising the Lombard rate.
Central banks move to ease strain of the D-Mark, Page 2
German economist warns of recession, Page 14
Fears eased by money supply rise, Page 7
Editorial Comment, Page 12
Lex, Page 14
Currencies and interest rates, Page 23
A rise in the UK money supply last month has reduced fears that the economy
may be sliding into further decline, though it provides little sign of an
upturn. M0, which mostly comprises notes and coins in circulation, increased
by 2.4 per cent in the 12 months to the end of July, after a year-on-year
rise of 1.3 per cent in June and 2.5 per cent in May. Report, Page 7
</TEXT>
