<HEADLINE>
FT  21 AUG 92 / Treasury to sell Pounds 1bn of privatised company debt
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN and MAGGIE URRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT is to use an innovative auction process to sell Pounds 1bn of
its approximately Pounds 5bn of loans made to privatised utility companies.
Under proposals unveiled yesterday, borrowers including BT and a string of
regional electricity companies and power generators, will be invited to bid
against each other to repurchase and retire their debt. The Treasury will
select which bonds to sell, allowing the repurchase only of complete issues
of debt. The sale will take place by the end of the current financial year.
Companies which buy back their debts may not achieve significant interest
savings despite the fall in interest rates since privatisation. Even if the
effect was neutral, however, they would be released from restrictive
covenants, gaining greater control over their finances.
Baring Brothers, the merchant bank appointed to advise the Treasury on the
sale, said it could not find any record of debt being sold in this way
before.
'We have developed a structure that takes full account of the market value,'
said Mr Cliff Haddy, a Barings assistant director. 'The companies are not
getting it on the cheap.'
The proceeds will count towards the Treasury's target of Pounds 8bn in
privatisation proceeds for the current financial year. The sale plan calls
for the creation of two bidding pools comprising, on the one hand, the
electricity companies, and, on the other, BT and interested third parties.
The structure was dictated partly because the government has undertaken not
to sell to third parties debt owed by the regional electricity companies
before the beginning of next year.
Barings said its proposals were also cheaper than the alternative of selling
loans to third parties, since marketing and underwriting fees would not be
incurred.
All told, the government estimates that some Pounds 3.74bn of its loan
assets are marketable, comprising Pounds 1.69bn of BT loan stock and Pounds
2.05bn of electricity company debt.
Individual loans range in size from a Pounds 350m debt owed by National
Power to small loans of less than Pounds 50m. Maturity dates stretch from
1997 to 2008. The debt was originally injected to give the privatised
companies what was deemed to be an appropriate capital structure.
Many of the electricity groups concerned said they could not comment on the
sale until they had studied the details of the auction process and had
further discussions with the Treasury, Barings and their own advisers.
