<HEADLINE>
FT  20 AUG 92 / MMC to investigate wholesale distribution of newspapers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GARY MEAD, Marketing Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE OFFICE of Fair Trading asked the Monopolies and Mergers Commission
yesterday to investigate the wholesale distribution of national newspapers
in England and Wales after complaints from independent retailers and MPs
that practices restrict competition.
The OFT said it was particularly concerned about barriers to entry into
retail newspaper sales. The main wholesale suppliers can currently refuse to
supply newspapers to shopkeepers who wish to set up new retail outlets.
The MMC would be expected to report to the trade and industry secretary in a
year.
Wholesale newspaper distribution was first referred to the MMC in 1976. Its
report two years later found a complex monopoly existed in favour of WH
Smith, John Menzies and Surridge Dawson - still the three largest wholesale
distributors - and a few smaller companies, but concluded it was not against
the public interest to limit the number of retailers. The subject was
reviewed in 1986 and again in September 1991, when the OFT decided that a
further referral to the MMC was unwarranted.
In 1988, distribution switched from rail to road and exclusive contracts
began to be awarded by some newspaper publishers to wholesalers.
That has resulted in retailers in many areas having only one of the main
wholesalers as a supplier. Retailers who have been denied supply have the
right to appeal to the publishers and wholesalers.
However, according to Mr Alan Taylor, national secretary of the British
Independent Grocers' Association, representing some 2,000 independent
retailers, the appeals system has failed: 'An application from a small
convenience store will be dealt with by a letter stating that 'the area is
adequately served'. But if you happen to be Dillons or Tesco, they usually
decide your area isn't adequately served. Strange, isn't it?'
Mr Ranald Noel-Paton, managing director of John Menzies, with some 20 per
cent of the market, denied his company restricted retail growth: 'We spend
all our time seeking ways to promote sales of newspapers. You do not do that
by cutting a finite cake into ever decreasing slices.'
WH Smith, which has some 27 per cent of the market, said: 'We have been down
this road before and we are quite happy to co-operate with the OFT again.'
Smith shares fall, Page 34
</TEXT>
