<HEADLINE>
FT  20 AUG 92 / Watchdog warns on council tax changes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government has been warned against making last-minute changes to the
council tax by the Audit Commission, the local authority watchdog.
In its annual report for the year ending March 31, the commission says the
timetable for introducing the tax - which replaces the poll tax, or
community charge, next April - is 'exceptionally short'.
This has meant local authorities faced a tight schedule for writing the
software for collection of the council tax, training staff to operate the
systems and providing information to the public on the tax.
The commission says: 'It is particularly important that the government does
not introduce late amendments to the council tax procedures which will
require new software routines at a late stage in the process.' Software
problems contributed to difficulties when the poll tax was introduced.
The warning comes as pressure mounts for government action to ease the
introduction of the council tax. There have been calls to adjust the values
of homes on which bills will be calculated to reflect price falls since the
valuation date - April 1 last year.
Backbench Conservative MPs are also pressing for generous Treasury support
to ease the introduction of the tax. Local authority leaders, though, have
backed the commission's warning and urged the government not to indulge in
'last-gasp intervention' to try to keep bills down.
Mr Jeremy Beecham, chairman of the Labour-controlled Association of
Metropolitan Authorities, said late government interference in two of the
three years of the poll tax had discredited the system and compounded
tax-collection difficulties for local authorities.
'If the government panics again and changes the council tax in a bid to keep
bills down, it could kill the tax in its infancy and fatally undermine any
future system of local government finance by creating a culture of
non-payment,' said Mr Beecham.
'Local government will cope with the introduction of the council tax, but
only if the government keeps its hands to itself and does not interfere
simply because it wants to placate its backbenchers.'
A lack of reliable management information in the National Health Service is
a significant obstacle to progress, according to the Audit Commission, which
is also responsible for auditing health authorities.
Financial controls and systems are sometimes 'rather basic' and there are
still too few good finance staff, the commission says.
Meanwhile, Labour has attacked government plans to announce today a further
150 applications for hospital trust status - the third wave due to become
operational in April next year. Ministers will also invite applications for
a fourth wave of trusts.
Audit Commission report and accounts for year ended March 31 1992. HMSO.
Pounds 8.50.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
