<HEADLINE>
FT  20 AUG 92 / Names lose campaign to have case heard in US
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LLOYD'S of London has scored a decisive victory in its legal battle with
dissident US Names.
In the US district court for the southern district of New York on Tuesday,
Judge Morris Lasker dismissed a case brought by some 100 Names  - the
individuals whose assets support underwriting at the insurance market. The
Names alleged that Lloyd's and the agents had breached US securities laws
when they were recruited. The Names started the action - the biggest Lloyd's
case involving US Names - last year.
Judge Lasker ruled, however, that the proper legal forum for any dispute
between the Names and Lloyd's was the English courts.
He said: 'Plaintiffs went to England to become members of a distinctively
British entity, invested in syndicates operating out of London and entered
numerous contracts, all of which stated plainly that Lloyd's affairs and
plaintiffs' investments would be administered in England and subject
exclusively to English law.'
He further found that the transactions into which plaintiffs had entered
with Lloyd's were truly international in character, thus making invalid
plaintiffs' arguments that such clauses illegally deprived them of the
protection of US securities laws.
In a 28-page opinion, Judge Lasker also held that while English laws might
not provide the same remedies as US laws, they were adequate for plaintiffs
to obtain relief.
'The sophistication and fairness of English courts cannot seriously be
challenged,' he said.
Judge Lasker concurred with findings in earlier cases heard by the Tenth
Circuit Court of Appeals and of the federal district court in Chicago, in
cases brought by other US Lloyd's Names. Because of the 'overwhelmingly'
English nature of the dispute, the judge concluded that it was likely he
would have reached the same decision as those other courts under the
doctrine of inconvenient forum - the legal rules under which it is decided
where cases are heard.
</TEXT>
