<HEADLINE>
FT  20 AUG 92 / Woolwich scheme lets 5,000 keep homes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE WOOLWICH, the third largest building society, said yesterday that its
in-house programme for those facing repossession has saved more than 5,000
mortgage holders from losing their homes since the start of the year.
The society, which has 512,300 mortgage customers, said the 5,000 were more
than 12 months in arrears with their payments and would normally have been
evicted.
Last year Woolwich repossessed 2,853 homes. So far this year its
repossessions are running about 20 per cent below last year's level.
Under the Woolwich scheme branches take responsibility for visiting
borrowers with serious arrears problems. Borrowers are encouraged to talk to
all the other lenders to whom they owe money and reschedule their debts.
The society said: 'We are looking after customers who cannot pay all their
mortgages but can pay some of what they owe.'
The 5,000 customers do not have a guarantee that they will never lose their
homes if they keep paying. The society merely says it expects at some stage
to be able to make permanent financial arrangements for them to keep their
homes.
Woolwich said it saw some hope over arrears. Its two-month arrears were
currently 20 per cent lower than they were a year ago and at their lowest
since February 1988.
