<HEADLINE>
FT  20 AUG 92 / Retail sales volume falls 0.3% in July
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE WEAK state of consumer demand was underlined yesterday by government
figures showing that retail sales volumes were 0.3 per cent lower last month
than in June.
The seasonally adjusted figures showed that people were still refraining
from spending in most categories of stores and that the small high-street
upturn that followed the Conservative general election victory was
short-lived.
Spending on food fell for the second consecutive month while spending in
shops selling both food and other goods fell to its lowest volume for six
months. The only sector to show an increase was clothing and footwear -
probably reflecting the marked price discounting that helped cut headline
inflation in July.
The gloomy picture is lightened by the underlying trend. Retail sales showed
a rise of 0.3 per cent in the three months ending on July 31 compared with
the previous three months. In the three months to the end of July volumes
were up by 0.5 per cent compared with the corresponding period last year.
This rise may be due mainly to the boost in consumer spending in the two
months after the April election. Revised figures for the three months to
June indicate a 0.8 per cent increase in volumes in April compared with
March. That was followed by flat demand in May and June.
Between May and July spending in food shops showed a 0.5 per cent increase
compared with the previous three months. Spending in shops which sell food
and other items showed a 0.7 per cent fall on a three-monthly basis.
Non-food sector spending rose 0.5 per cent over the last three months. Sales
of household goods were down 1 per cent.
The British Retail Consortium said retailing continued to be highly
competitive. It added that July's sales were above those in July last year
in value and only just down in volume. 'The fortunes of retailers are
unlikely to improve significantly until consumer confidence returns and the
housing market improves,' the consortium said.
