FT  20 AUG 92 / BA cabin crews to continue strikes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CABIN-CREW members of the TGWU union employed by British Airways in
Manchester and Birmingham said yesterday that they would press ahead with
their programme of one-day strikes.
They will also vote on whether to take action short of strikes.
The decision, by about 500 crew, came as the airline threatened to suspend
without pay any crew member who went on strike. This followed an improved
offer from BA worth a total of about Pounds 1,000.
Local union officials warned that action would spread to Heathrow, Gatwick,
Belfast and Glasgow should the airline suspend staff.
Seven flights were grounded after strikes at Birmingham and Manchester
earlier this month. Crew elsewhere refrained from action, partly because 221
crew are pursuing legal actions for breach of contract against BA.
The union says the airline imposed worse terms and conditions on crew
without notice, and members would prefer to settle the case through the
courts. BA has offered an out-of-court settlement of Pounds 425 per crew
member.
Under the new terms and conditions about 1,000 staff face pay cuts of Pounds
2,000 on salaries of Pounds 14,000 a year. Next year crews would receive pay
rises only if inflation was above 4 per cent.
The new terms follow a cost-cutting reorganisation of BA shorthaul
operations.
BA said it had not been notified of the planned action and stood by its new
offer.
</TEXT>
