<HEADLINE>
FT  20 AUG 92 / Speculation mounts over cabinet hit-list: Republican Party
Convention in Houston
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN, US Editor
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HOUSTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Nicholas Brady, US treasury secretary, said yesterday he accepted that
President George Bush would want to reshuffle his cabinet if he won a second
term, but he had not talked to the president personally about leaving,
writes Jurek Martin, US Editor, in Houston.
His remarks were in response to a flurry of speculation generated on Tuesday
night when Mr Bush said in a television interview: 'You'll see plenty of new
faces, plenty of changes in this administration.'
The instant assumption was that Mr Brady, Mr Richard Darman, the budget
director, and Mr Michael Boskin, chairman of the council of economic
advisers, would go, as long demanded by right-wing Republicans dissatisfied
with the performance of the economy.
Of these, only Mr Boskin has previously indicated a desire to leave his
post, although Mr Brady said it was within the president's prerogative to
make changes he wanted and that a second term was a logical time to make
such moves. This was coupled to a report in the New York Times that Mr Bush
was considering keeping Mr James Baker at the White House in a second term,
to serve as overall economic policy chief.
Mr Baker, secretary of state until Sunday when he becomes Mr Bush's chief of
staff and campaign manager, was reported to be resistant to the idea on the
grounds that it was 'too gimmicky'. His return to control over foreign
policy had previously been considered the most likely option should Mr Bush
win in November.
The White House yesterday denied rumours that Mr Jack Kemp, the outspoken
housing secretary, was also on the potential hit-list. His departure would
upset the right and might be interpreted as ingratitude after Mr Kemp's
effusive endorsement of the president in a speech to the party's convention
on Tuesday night.
Mr Bush's main purpose in his television interview, as in many others
recently, has been to demonstrate he is as committed to 'change' as is Mr
Bill Clinton, his Democratic rival. This will be an important theme of his
acceptance speech tonight, in which he is said to be contemplating an
announcement about Mr Baker's long-term future.
But Mr Clinton was quick to latch on to the president's plan for cabinet
changes, saying it was an acknowledgement that Mr Bush's current team had
failed.
Changing the composition of his economics team would demonstrate that on
domestic affairs the president is prepared to turn over a new leaf. Of even
greater immediate interest tonight is the extent to which he will commit
himself to tax cuts.
The risks of going out on a limb and making an unsustainable promise
comparable to his 'read my lips, no new taxes,' pledge of four years ago are
well understood. The more likely approach is a general commitment to
reducing taxes in a second term as progress is made towards cutting the
federal budget deficit.
But this middle way might be seen as ineffective, much as Mr Bush's past
speeches on the economy have been.
An ABC News-Washington Post poll released yesterday, the first nationwide
survey of voting preferences conducted since the party's convention opened,
showed Mr Bush dropped two points in the last week, leaving him trailing Mr
Clinton by 58 to 33 per cent. Republican leaders had forecast Mr Clinton's
lead would be halved by the convention's conclusion.
</TEXT>
