FT  20 AUG 92 / World Trade News: Israel and China aim to boost trade
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY WALKER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JERUSALEM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ISRAEL and China yesterday initialled a trade agreement Israeli officials
hope will facilitate increased exports of such items as electronic goods and
farm equipment, Tony Walker writes from Jerusalem. The pact follows the
setting-up of formal relations in January and comes amid increased trade
contacts between the two countries.
Mr Zvi Koren, director-general of Israel's industry and trade ministry, said
the protocol would enable Israel to 'enter the Chinese market directly and
smoothly, without barriers'. Israel's 'visible' exports to China are
expected to reach Dollars 30m this year, against imports of Dollars 4m.
Israeli companies have also been involved in selling military equipment and
know-how to China.
Much of Israel's trade with China has been routed through third countries.
Mr Koren said a 'co-ordinating committee' would start to deal with such
issues as investment insurance, double taxation and copyright.
El Al, Israel's national carrier, will begin direct once-weekly flights from
Tel Aviv to Beijing next month, it said yesterday.
