</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INTERNATIONAL investors have subscribed Dollars 30.8m for the first
closed-end Czechoslovak country fund, seven months after the fund was
launched with the aim of raising Dollars 100m, writes Richard Waters.
The delay and low level of subscription were caused by uncertainty over the
country's future, said Robert Fleming, the manager of the fund. The
fragmentation of Yugoslavia had left many potential investors concerned
about the aftermath of a division of Czechoslovakia, it said.
Investments will initially be made in the Czech republic, though Fleming
does not rule out investments in Slovakia. The European Bank for
Reconstruction and Development, which has two seats on the board of the
Czechoslovakia Investment Corporation, committed Dollars 10m of the capital.
